Once again the SU is moaning about us providing basic scrutiny. These are a group of people who have become essentially unaccountable and so are pushing back at the once last check on their authority. It's a bit annoying then, that some people here are breaking ranks and liking their posts. The news team works unbelievably hard to turn out the content it does and hold all university institutions to account, so the very least you can do is to not be a scab and have the paper's back.

#Varsitea79

The real problem is in the past few years the paper has failed to hold the SU to account over literally anything (with the exception of a couple of articles last term). This means the Sabbs can whinge and act as though what we're doing is unprecedented, even if covering student reaction is the bare minimum of what a student newspaper should do.  Our SU coverage is celebrated by many people within the SU, who want the institution to succeed, except for the Sabbs who enjoy having zero checks on their authority.

#Varsitea99 

With regret I have to use this platform to make a statement about a libellous "Varsitea" that has been published today by "Varsitea" . I am currently in hospital with family, expecting the imminent passing of a dear relative. In full knowledge of my personal circumstances, anonymous users have chosen to write multiple "varsiteas" in which they have made serious false allegations about me. 

One action they attributed to me is so distorted and mischaracterised as to be untrue: they suggested I was a "scab" for liking an SU post. I would never intentionally like a post by this student's "union". I accidentally pressed the "like" button on their facebook page. As soon as I was made aware of this grievous error, I "unliked" the aforementioned post. 

The other allegation is a complete fabrication: they suggested I "wrote half of today's 'Varsiteas'". In reality, I posted all of them. There are numerous people (one) who are prepared to corroborate this. 

That I am writing this rather than focusing on my family at this time is a source of immeasurable pain, and it will tarnish this memory forever. But I know how these things work, and so I thought it important to say something publicly. Varsitea asked me for comment as I travelled home; I explained my situation and stated too that the claims made were untrue. I recognise that my societal positions carry with them a degree of exposure, but that does not make character assassinations like the one I am on the receiving end of at all justifiable.

 That Varsitea chose specifically to do so whilst I am in hospital is deeply inhumane. I have spoken to a lawyer and will be following up as I take the implications of this false attribution very seriously. But for now, I would like to spend time with my family. I would greatly appreciate if I could be afforded the privacy at this time that Varsitea declined to give me.

Truly unbelievable journalistic standards at Varsitea. A post *entirely* researched via Varsitea comments actually quotes my FB comment saying I don't have a piss fetish! No direct contact with me, no research on current fetish trends, just pure reactionary Daily Mail style manufactured outrage commentary. 

Piss fetishists absolutely need critical student journalism to hold us to account and to report on how we're doing, whether we're getting it right or not. But in order to serve  students best, we need journalism that prioritises accuracy and integrity over boiling piss.

If Varsitea would like to bother to reach out and give us the chance to provide a comment to them directly before publishing an article on our work, I am still more than happy to engage. And as always, I will always find time to have meetings with any student who has concerns or feedback about how I'm pissing (away all the SU's money xd) so please do get in touch directly also.
